    short: 'Take 1 stress to give an ally +1d — but you are now exposed to the consequences too.',
    body: 'Another PC is rolling. You describe how you help, take **1 stress**, and they get **+1 die**.\n\nThe catch is fictional and it is real: by helping, **you are now in the scene and exposed to the consequences**. If the roll goes wrong, the GM can put the harm, the complication or the blame on you instead of — or as well as — the roller.\n\nOnly **one assist per roll per helper**, but **multiple characters may each assist**, each for 1 stress and +1d.\n\nAn assist needs a **concrete fictional action**: "I brace the door", "I call out the guard\'s position", "I keep the mark talking". Cheerleading is not an assist.\n\nCompare a **setup action**, which is a roll of your own that improves the ally\'s **position or effect** instead of handing them a die. Setups are stronger and slower; assists are instant and cheap.',
