    short: 'Roll an action of your own to improve a teammate\'s position OR effect on their following roll.',
    body: 'A **setup action** is your own **action roll**, made to prepare the ground for someone else. Distract the guard, pick the lock ahead of the runner, sway the target into a receptive mood.\n\nOn a **success**, the teammate\'s next roll gets **+1 position** *or* **+1 effect** — you pick which when you set it up.\n\nOn a **4–5** you still get it, plus a consequence. On a **1–3** the setup fails and things get worse.\n\nSetups are **more powerful than assists** because a position or effect bump changes the outcome, not the odds — but they **cost you a roll**, expose you to your own consequences, and must come **before** the ally acts.\n\nSetups **chain**: one PC sets up another, who sets up a third. A well-built chain can take a desperate/limited job and turn it into a controlled/great one, which is what a good crew looks like when it is working.',
