    short: 'Everyone rolls the same action; use the single best result, and the leader takes 1 stress per failed roll.',
    body: 'When the whole crew does the same thing at once — everyone sneaks past, everyone climbs the wall, everyone holds their nerve — one PC **leads** the group action.\n\n· **Everyone rolls** the same action.\n· The **single best result** counts for the entire group.\n· The **leader takes 1 stress for each roll that failed (1–3)**.\n\nThat stress is the price of coordinating a crew of criminals, and it scales viciously: a five-person group action with three failures costs the leader **3 stress**, a third of their track, before anything has even gone wrong.\n\nEveryone shares the outcome — if the best roll was a 4–5, the **whole group** succeeds with the consequence.\n\nUse group actions when the fiction genuinely requires everyone to do the thing. If one person can do it while others help, that is an **assist** and it is cheaper.',
