    kind: 'mechanic',
    short: 'A circle divided into 4, 6, or 8 segments that tracks progress or looming danger; successes fill segments by effect level.',
    body: 'A **progress clock** is how Blades measures anything that takes more than one roll. Draw a circle, divide it into **4, 6, or 8 segments**, and name it.\n\nFill segments on a success, sized by **effect**:\n\n· **Limited effect** — 1 segment\n· **Standard effect** — 2 segments\n· **Great effect** — 3 segments\n\nWhen it fills, the thing happens. Clock sizes signal scope: **4** is a short obstacle, **6** a real task, **8** a serious undertaking.\n\nThe varieties you\'ll actually use:\n\n· **Danger clocks** — the alarm is raised, the ritual completes, the Bluecoats arrive. These tick up on your **consequences**.\n· **Racing clocks** — two clocks side by side, yours and theirs. Whoever fills first wins.\n· **Linked clocks** — filling one starts or unlocks another.\n· **Long-term project clocks** — usually 8+ segments, filled during **downtime**.\n· **Healing clock** — filled by the **Recover** downtime activity.\n\nClocks should be **visible on the table**. A hidden clock is just the GM deciding; a visible one is pressure the players can feel and plan around.',
