    kind: 'condition',
    short: 'Injury written as words on a 4-level tracker, not numbers: less effect, −1d, need help, then fatal.',
    body: '**Harm** is never a number. You **write what happened** on your harm tracker at the level the GM assigns, and the level tells you what it costs:\n\n· **Level 1 — Lesser** (two boxes): **reduced effect** on relevant actions. *"Battered", "Drained", "Distracted".*\n· **Level 2 — Moderate** (two boxes): **−1d** to relevant rolls. *"Broken Arm", "Deep Cut", "Terrified".*\n· **Level 3 — Severe** (one box): you **need help** to act at all in that area. *"Impaled", "Shattered Leg".*\n· **Level 4 — Fatal**: you are **dead or permanently taken out** unless you **resist**.\n\nHarm only applies **when it is relevant** — a "Broken Arm" doesn\'t penalise your Sway. That is the whole reason harm is words instead of hit points.\n\n**If a level\'s boxes are full**, new harm at that level **moves up a level instead**. Two Lesser harms and a third one arriving means you now have a **Moderate**. This is how a character dies from a thousand cuts.\n\nBefore harm is written, you may **resist** it (paying stress) to reduce it a level or avoid it, or check an **armour** box if it applies. Once written, it comes off only through the **Recover** downtime activity and a **healing clock**.',
    seeAlso: ['Resistance Roll', 'Armour', 'Recover', 'Healing Clock', 'Consequence'],
